# Dependencies

- Add dependencies with the package manager (`npm install`), never by hand-editing version strings. Commit the updated `package-lock.json`.
- Prefer extending what is already installed over adding a new package. Justify every new dependency in the plan.
- Update dependencies one at a time and re-run `typecheck`, `lint`, and `test` after each. Group successful updates into a single `chore(deps):` commit. Flag major-version bumps for human review.
- Treat `npm audit` findings at `high` or above as blockers. The CI dependency-audit step enforces this.

# Dependabot guidance

- `react` and `react-dom` must always be updated together — the `react-runtime` group in `dependabot.yml` batches them into a single PR.
- Do not merge a grouped dev-dependency PR that fails CI; close it and update packages individually.
- ESLint major bumps (`eslint`, `@eslint/js`, `typescript-eslint`) require an explicit plugin-compatibility check before merging — `eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y` and similar plugins frequently cap at the previous major. Dependabot ignores these by default; perform them manually when ready.

# Third-party rules, skills, and MCP servers

- Rules, skills, and MCP servers are executable instructions and a supply-chain surface. Read any you import before trusting it.
- MCP servers must be allowlisted deliberately in `.cursor/mcp.json`. Do not add a server, or widen its scope, without explicit approval. Prefer read-only/least-privilege configurations.
- Never pass secrets to an MCP server through prompts or arguments; use environment variables the server reads itself.

# Deterministic enforcement (do not bypass)

- Cursor hooks in `.cursor/hooks.json` gate shell commands and file reads at runtime; pre-commit (husky + gitleaks) and CI (typecheck, lint, test, build, audit, secret scan, SAST) gate every change. Do not disable, weaken, or work around these to get a change through — fix the underlying issue.
